I always keep an eye on what the world’s best investors are buying and selling…

Think of the stock market like a big store where people can buy and sell pieces of ownership in companies. Sometimes, there are people called “institutional investment managers” who buy and sell a lot of these pieces for other people.

A few examples of institutional money managers you might know are Warren Buffett, Bill Ackman, and Cathie Wood.

Every three months, these institutional investment managers have to tell the government what pieces of companies they have bought and sold. This is called a “form 13-F disclosure”.

These are important because when we look at these disclosures, we can see which companies the institutional investment managers like and which ones they don’t like so much. This can give us an idea of what companies might be good to buy pieces of, or what companies we might want to avoid.

While form 13-F disclosures are delayed and should NOT be the sole reason for buying and selling a stock, they can help us make better decisions about what we’re buying and selling.

The Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) is the group within the Fed that is responsible for setting monetary policy. It meets several times a year to discuss the state of the economy and make decisions about interest rates and other monetary policy tools.

During FOMC meetings, members review economic data and projections, such as inflation, employment, and GDP growth, to assess the current state of the economy. They then decide whether to adjust the target range for the federal funds rate, which is the interest rate at which banks lend to each other overnight.

In 2022, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates at their fastest pace in 40 years. This was a key reason stocks, bonds, and crypto had one of their worst years on record. 

Prior to the regional banking crisis that began on March 10, it was widely expected that the Fed would announce a 0.50% rate increase. 

But since it seems the banking industry is unable to bear the weight of these higher rates, many economists now expect the Fed to only hike 0.25% or even 0% at tomorrow’s meeting.

I am expecting a 0.25% hike tomorrow, but also expect Powell to announce a “pause” on rate hikes. 

But if the Fed surprises to the upside, expect some fireworks to the downside for all risk assets.

Lots of bad takes about the US dollar losing its reserve currency status going around…
.
.
.
.
.
…but here are the facts. 

The dollar has lost some ground to competing currencies over the last few decades. 

But as the chart shows, it’s only a 12% drop in 22 years, so nothing to be worried about.

During the Global Financial Crisis, the COVID-19 Pandemic, and the Russian invasion of Ukraine, investors flooded into US dollars as it’s still considered a “safe haven” currency. 

That is because by buying dollars, one can also buy US government bonds, which are also seen as a safe haven. 

In terms of overall international currency usage, the US dollar remains by far the most used currency with the euro in distance second (and the Chinese yuan barely visible on the chart).

The dollar's role as the global reserve currency isn't changing anytime soon. 

These calls for “de-dollarization” are nothing new and crop up during every financial crisis.

I'm not saying the US and its currency are perfect. 

The US dollar is simply the best choice among a lot of bad options. 

This is a key reason every country on Earth holds dollars in their foreign currency reserves.

This bitcoin rally reminds me a lot of the rally in 2019…

Bitcoin had a massive rally from 2017-2018 with the cryptocurrency rising over 1,000%.

This ended with a crash in 2018 that sent bitcoin down -73%. 

This 2018 crash was due to the Federal Reserve hiking interest rates and the trade war with China. But it was followed by a rally in 2019 due to the Fed lowering interest rates, sending bitcoin up +260%.

Sound familiar? 

Bitcoin saw a massive rally from 2020-2021, rising over 1,000% from the COVID Crash lows to its $60,000 peak in late 2021.

This ended with a crash in 2022 that sent bitcoin down -64%.

The 2022 crash was due to the Fed hiking interest rates and Russia invading Ukraine. And now with investors expecting the Fed to cut interest rates this summer (see chart), we’ve seen a huge rally sending bitcoin +85%. 

I am optimistic that this is the early stages of a new bull run. But that doesn’t mean bitcoin will go up in a straight line. Crypto is highly volatile, so if you plan to invest only invest money you can afford to lose.

And if your investments are keeping you awake at night, you’ve invested too much. 

But to me, the long-term trend for bitcoin appears to be “up.”

Three of the four largest bank failures in US history have happened in the last two months… 

Despite this, the S&P 500 has actually increased by 6% since the crisis began with Silicon Valley Bank on March 12.

The reason for this is due to actions by the Federal Reserve. 

The three troubled banks had deposit bases closely linked to startup firms in the tech industry, many of which tripled in size during the pandemic-era tech boom. 

However, instead of investing all of the deposits into other startups or venture firms, these banks placed a sizable share of the funds into long-term Treasury bonds and mortgage bonds, which typically deliver small but reliable returns amid low interest rates.

This strategy worked until inflation started to rage out of control in 2021 and 2022 when prices rose at their fastest pace in 40 years. 

To combat inflation, the Federal Reserve had to raise interest rates fast, which sent the yield on long-term Treasury bonds soaring. 

As yields and price move inversely to each other, the value of the Treasury bonds bought by Silicon Valley Bank, Signature Bank, and First Republic collapsed in value.

In late February, rumors began circulating on social media that Silicon Valley Bank and others were insolvent, which kicked off a classic "bank run" when customers all attempted to withdraw their money at the same time. 

However, since these deposits were tied up in Treasury bonds that were deeply in the red, the bank would have had to sell them at a loss to give people their money back.

There are several other banks facing the same issue, so it's possible that we will see more bank failures in the near future. 

The Federal Reserve and larger banks like JP Morgan Chase are stepping in to add "liquidity" to the system, acquire struggling banks, and prevent further collapses, but it's uncertain how effective this approach will be in the long run.

Happy 13-F day to those who celebrate...

Form 13-F is a quarterly report filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) by institutional investment managers with over $100 million in assets under management. 

It reveals their stock holdings at the end of the previous quarter, providing insight into the investments made by the world's best fund managers.

While I keep a close eye on form 13-F releases, I wouldn't recommend copying them verbatim.

For one, these forms are delayed by many months. Market conditions can change rapidly, and what was a great investment then might not be the same now. 

Second, investors may have made changes since the filing date and may not hold the positions listed. 

Third, these investors may not share your risk profile, time frame, or investing goals. 

Knowing all that, you may be asking why look at them at all? 

I look at these filings to get investing ideas and often find lesser-known companies that have piqued the interest of some of the world's top investors. 

Plus, you get to see which companies or broader investing trends the best investors on the planet have their eye on.

So while I would not simply copy these investments, I would pay attention to them as a piece of the broader investing puzzle.

Did you know there’s a rule called the 28/36 rule to help you figure it out? 

Here’s how it works: Your monthly mortgage, property tax, and insurance costs shouldn’t exceed 28% of your gross income.

Let’s break it down. Say you make $80,000 per year, that means your housing expenses shouldn’t go beyond $1,866 per month.

And for those earning $200,000 annually, keep your max housing costs below $4,666 per month. 

But what does that translate to in terms of housing prices? Assuming a 20% down payment and a 30-year fixed mortgage at a 6.8% interest rate, someone earning $80,000 can afford a $250,000 house.

And if your salary hits $200,000, your budget could stretch to a $670,000 house. 🏠

Everyone wants to focus on how to make money and to get that “home run” trade.

But especially for new investors, your focus should be on not losing money.

Because if you keep your losses small, the upside will take care of itself. 

This sentiment has been echoed by the world's greatest investors, including Warren Buffett, Stanley Druckenmiller, and Paul Tudor Jones.

And it makes sense why: the math is not in the loser’s favor. 

The table above shows that the more your losses increase, the gains required to breakeven increase exponentially, as the math gets less favorable the more you lose.

For example, if a position in your portfolio falls by 50%, that position needs to rise 100% just to breakeven. 

And if a portfolio position falls 90%, you need to make a 900% gain just to get back to even.

This is why minimizing losses is so important. If you can avoid big losses, you can avoid the need for big gains just to breakeven.

There’s actually a psychological reason why people don’t do this called the disposition effect.

That occurs when investors are reluctant to sell stocks that are down but more likely to sell stocks that have gone up. 

While it’s a hard lesson to learn, you don't do yourself any favors by hanging onto losing positions.

And when I see people in our investing community doing this, I often send them this quote from Peter Lynch:

"Selling your winners and holding your losers is like cutting your flowers and watering your weeds."

Instead of succumbing to the disposition effect, the best thing to do is take the loss and move on.

Form 13-F is a quarterly report filed with the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) by institutional investment managers with over $100
million in assets under management.

It reveals their stock holdings at the end of the previous quarter, providing insight into the investments made by the world's best fund managers.

While I keep a close eye on form 13-F releases, I wouldn't recommend copying them verbatim.

For one, these forms are delayed by many months.
Market conditions can change rapidly, and what was a great investment then might not be the same now.

Second, investors may have made changes since the filing date and may not hold the positions listed.

Third, these investors may not share your risk profile, time frame, or investing goals.
Knowing all that, you may be asking why look at them at all?
1 look at these filings to get investing ideas and often find lesser-known companies that have piqued the interest of some of the world's top investors.

Plus, you get to see which companies or broader investing trends the best investors on the planet have their eye on.

So while I would not simply copy these investments, would pay attention to them as a piece of the broader investing puzzle.

Billionaire hedge fund managers Bill Ackman made a name for himself as an “activist investor.”

An activist investor is a shareholder who uses their stake in a company to push for changes they believe will increase shareholder value. 

Unlike typical investors who invest passively, activist investors are proactive, often seeking to influence or change company policies, financial strategies, management, or board composition. 

The goal is to improve the company’s performance and, consequently, its stock price, benefiting all shareholders.

Lots of talk about “late stage capitalism” lately.

But the economic system gets a bad rap.

For instance, capitalism has lifted millions out of poverty.

The percentage of the world’s population living in extreme poverty fell from 36% in 1990 to 10% in 2015, largely due to market-driven economies (Source: World Bank).

Capitalist economies often see higher standards of living. 

Competition and profit motives lead to improved technologies and services, enhancing everyday life (Source: “Capital in the Twenty-First Century” by Thomas Piketty).

Capitalism also supports personal freedom, allowing individuals to choose their careers, where to invest, and what to buy. 

This freedom is a cornerstone of democratic societies.

Capitalism isn’t perfect, but it’s the best system we have.
